You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput microservice intermittently hangs, consumes 100% CPU, or throws `ConcurrentModificationException` under high concurrent load. A review of the codebase reveals the following custom cache implementation inside a Spring singleton bean:

java
@Service
public class MetricCache {
    private final Map<MetricKey, MetricValue> cache = 
        Collections.synchronizedMap(new WeakHashMap<>());

    public MetricValue getMetric(MetricKey key) {
        return cache.computeIfAbsent(key, this::loadFromDatabase);
    }

    private MetricValue loadFromDatabase(MetricKey key) {
        return new MetricValue(); // Simulates fetching from DB
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where a Spring Boot application throws a `LazyInitializationException` inside an asynchronous event listener. The developer attempted to solve this by wrapping a Hibernate-managed lazy collection (`PersistentBag`) in a custom thread-safe decorator that invokes `size()` to eagerly initialize the collection inside the `@Transactional` boundary before passing it to an `@Async` method:

java
@Transactional
public void processOrder(Long orderId) {
    Order order = orderRepository.findById(orderId).orElseThrow();
    List<OrderItem> items = new EagerlyInitializedList<>(order.getItems()); // Custom decorator calling size()
    eventPublisher.publishAsyncEvent(items);
}
